  "name": "cbn-bochner-stratus-oem-strategy-1982-06-245fd5",
  "title": "Computer Business News: Stratus Banks on Fault-Tolerant Systems' Success \u2014 Pete Kastner on OEM Strategy and Second-Generation Roadmap (June 7, 1982)",
  "description": "June 7, 1982 Computer Business News page-8 cover-class feature by Peter Bochner on Stratus Computer's fault-tolerant systems strategy. Pete Kastner \u2014 quoted as 'Stratus' manager of marketing development' \u2014 outlines the most extensive publicly-recorded Stratus strategy of the era: (1) OEM channel: 'any company starting out that ignores OEMs is ignoring a big opportunity'; software houses earn a fee on each Stratus system sold incorporating their software; (2) competitive positioning: Stratus/32 pits against the Prime 750, DEC VAX 11/750 and IBM 4341 Model 1 on price/performance, NOT directly head-to-head with Tandem; (3) second-generation plans: at least a year away, will maintain back-compatibility, may use a different CPU via code-generator change to protect user software investment; (4) industry forecast: by 1986 'all broad-based computer companies will have to offer fault-tolerant systems' and at least half a dozen will be shipping by end of 1983; (5) market thesis: fault-tolerant 'blossoming from a niche market to a cross market' as more work goes online and downtime cost rises. Bochner notes Kastner is 'a former analyst at Arthur D. Little' \u2014 the FIRST appearance of Kastner's ADL background in the Aberdeen archive. The article also covers Stratus 3270 emulator, X.25 Networking, four-68000-chip CPU pairing, 7%/yr maintenance vs industry 10-12%/yr, remote diagnostics, and Edson de Castro of DG warning startups have problems shipping second-gen products.",
